Mountain Will Come: Arabic Letters -- tIf the Mountain Will Not Come: Official Inscriptions -- tUmayyad Official Documentary Standard as Early Islamic Documentary Standard -- tConclusion -- tIV A Culture of Ambivalence -- tNegotiating “Arab Style” -- tShifting Boundaries between Scribal Cultures in the Umayyad Empire -- tParallel Scribal Traditions: Numismatics -- tParallel Scribal Traditions: Independent Arab-Style Scribal Practices -- tConclusion -- tV An Empire of Words -- tRegional Idiolects in the Use of Administrative Loanwords in Documentary Arabic -- tThe Loanwords in Imperial Arabic (640–800) -- tRegional Diversity in the Use of Administrative Loanwords in Early Islamic Documentary Arabic -- tTerminology and Regional Settings: The Role of Umayyad Syria and the Looming Shadow of Abbasid Iraq -- tConclusion -- tSummary and Conclusions -- tAppendices -- tAppendix 1: Formal and Layout Structure of Early Islamic Arabic Official Letters -- tAppendix 2: Formal and Layout Structure of Early Islamic Official Inscriptions -- tAppendix 3: Comparative Table of Early Islamic Arab-style Letters -- tBibliography -- tIndices -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex Locorum I: Papyri -- tIndex Locorum II: Inscriptions0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSeventh and eighth-century papyri, inscriptions, and coins constitute the main evidence for the rise of Arabic as a hegemonic language emerging from the complex fabric of Graeco-Roman-Iranian Late Antiquity. This volume examines these sources in order to gauge the social ecology of Arabic writing within the broader late antique continuum. Starting from the functional interplay of Arabic with other languages in multilingual archives as well as the mediality of practices of public Arabic writing, the study correlates the rise of Arabic as an imperial language to social interactions: the negotiation between the Arab-Muslim imperial elite and non-Arabicized regional elites of the early Islamic empire. Using layout, formulae and technical terminology to trace common patterns and disruptions across sources from the Atlantic to Central Asia, the volume illuminates the distinctive formal varieties of official Umayyad and early Abbasid imperial documents compared to informal Arabic writings as well as to neighboring scribal traditions in other languages. The volume connects documentary practices to broader imperial policies, opening an unprecedented window into the strategies of governance that lay at the core of the early Islamic empire.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArabic languagexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aFrühislamisch. 4aKultur. 4aPapyrologie. 4aÜbergangszeit. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh  aArabic papyrology.  aCultural liminality and multiglossia.  aEarly Islamic Empire.  aRepresentation of authority.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z978311076682008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022 Englishz978311099454408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022z9783110994537oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107409740 cprintz978311074072140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311074082040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110740820423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110740820/original  a978-3-11-076682-0  DG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099454-4  EBO